	Measure for measure  
	Birla Industrial and Technological Museum (BITM) is hosting an exhibition, Measuring Our Planet, where one can learn first-hand how things like ultrasonic waves help to calculate the depth of oceans, photovoltaic cells detect sources of light and the hygrometer calculates atmospheric humidity. We have deliberately kept the level of the exhibition low to reach out to the maximum number of children. Instead of the usual themes of global warming and environment, we wanted to focus on something that would make people aware of the size, shape and character of the Earth, said BITM director Jayanta Sthanapati. The 25-exhibit display will travel to regional centres of the National Council of Science Museums, the parent body of BITM. You can come upon interesting information, like a manual on map-making written by Ptolemy in the Second Century AD, followed even in Renaissance engravings.The exhibition will be on from 10am to 5.30pm every day. Tickets are Rs 15 per head for the general public and Rs 7 per head for student groups.        
